flamininus] ‘Flaminius Codd. plerique’ (Halm), but Cicero is speaking of T. Quine- tius Flamininus, one of those who had triumphed for their Macedonian victories.

Esquilinam] Here he trampled on his bays (laurea) gained in Macedonia, where he had been saluted as Imperator; and then he went to his lodging near the Caelimon- tana: on which Manutius observes that Piso entered by the Esquilina and then went to the other gate. Cicero does not make the man say that he entered by the Esqui- lina.

em hac die biduo ante] A house or lodging hired two days before his entering the city, and the rent to be reckoned from the day of his entry. All this dull talk is to show what a mean fellow Piso was. But he was a prudent man if he did not hire a house before he wanted it.
